# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: charleston-south-carolina
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] The **1790 United States census** was the first United States census.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] It recorded the population of the whole United States as of Census Day, August 2, 1790, as mandated by Article 1, Section 2, of the Constitution and applicable laws.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] In the first census, the population of the United States was enumerated to be 3,929,214 inhabitants.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] Congress assigned responsibility for the 1790 census to the marshals of United States judicial districts under an act, which with minor modifications and extensions, governed census taking through the 1840 census.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] Both Secretary of State Thomas Jefferson and President George Washington expressed skepticism over the results, believing that the true population had been undercounted.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] If indeed an undercount was the result, possible explanations for it include dispersed population, poor transportation links, limitations of contemporary technology, and individual refusal to participate.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] Although the census was proved statistically factual, based on data collected, the records for several states (including Delaware, Georgia, New Jersey, and Virginia) were lost sometime between 1790 and 1830.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] Almost one-third of the original census data have been lost or destroyed since their original documentation.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1790 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] The census was not conducted in Vermont until 1791, after that state's admission to the Union as the 14th state on March 4 of that year.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] At 17.8 percent, the 1790 census's proportion of slaves to the free population was the highest ever recorded by any census of the United States.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] 0 is the correct figure, and the 16 here should be added to the "All other free persons" column.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] When the census of 1790 was published in 1791, it reported 16 slaves, which were illegal in Vermont.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] Subsequently, and up to 1860, the number is given as 17.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] An examination of the original manuscript by the Census Bureau superintendent found that there never were any slaves in Vermont.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] The original error occurred in preparing the results for publication, when 16 persons, returned as "Free colored," were classified as "Slave" in Bennington County.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 85,425, or 114 less than figures published in 1790, due to an error of addition of several towns.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 59,096, or 2 more than figures published in 1790, due to error in addition.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] The figures for Virginia do not include the population of Kentucky.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] Though Kentucky was then a part of Virginia, the Kentucky figures were compiled separately, and are shown on the line for Kentucky.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] The Virginia figures do include the portion of Virginia that later became the state of West Virginia.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1800-united-states-census] The **1800 United States census** was the second census conducted in the United States.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1800-united-states-census] It showed that 5,308,483 people were living in the United States, of whom 893,602 were slaves.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1800-united-states-census] The 1800 census included the new District of Columbia.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1800-united-states-census] The census for the following states were lost: Georgia, Kentucky, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1800-united-states-census] In comparison to the 1790 census, the 1800 census gathered additional information.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1800-united-states-census] The census was published in December 1801 and cost $66,109.04.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1800-united-states-census] This census is one of the several for which some of the original data are no longer available.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1800-united-states-census] Original census returns for Georgia, Kentucky, Mississippi, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia were lost over the years.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1800-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1800 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1810-united-states-census] The **1810 United States census** was the third census conducted in the United States.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1810-united-states-census] It showed that 7,239,881 people were living in the United States, of whom 1,191,362 were slaves.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1810-united-states-census] The 1810 census included one new state: Ohio.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1810-united-states-census] The original census returns for the District of Columbia, Georgia, Mississippi, New Jersey, and Ohio were lost or destroyed over the years.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1810-united-states-census] Most of Tennessee's original forms were also lost, other than Grainger and Rutherford counties.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1810-united-states-census] This was the last census with Virginia ranked as the most populous state.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1810-united-states-census] Census taking was not yet an exact science.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1810-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and some drew up their own, resulting in pages without headings.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1810-united-states-census] Some enumerators did not tally their results.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1810-united-states-census] As a result, census records for many towns before 1830 are idiosyncratic.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1810-united-states-census] This is not to suggest that they are less reliable than subsequent censuses, but that they may require more work on the part of the researcher.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1810-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1810 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] The **1820 United States census** was the fourth census conducted in the United States.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census included six new states: Louisiana, Indiana, Mississippi, Illinois, Alabama and Maine.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] There has been a district wide loss of 1820 census records for Arkansas Territory, Missouri Territory, and New Jersey.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] The total population was determined to be 9,638,453, of which 1,538,022 were slaves.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] The center of population was about 120 miles (193 km) west-northwest of Washington in Hardy County, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] This was the first census in which any states recorded a population of over one million—New York, Virginia, and Pennsylvania—as well as the first in which a city recorded a population of over 100,000—New York.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] Also, in this census and the 14 subsequent ones, New York was the most populous state until being superseded by California in the 1970 census.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census contains a great deal more information than previous censuses.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] Several of these columns were for special counts, and not to be included in the aggregate total.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] Doing so would have resulted in counting some individuals twice.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were asked to use double lines, red ink or some other method of distinguishing these columns so that double counting would not occur.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] For example, the count of free white males between 16 and 18 was a special count, because these individuals were also supposed to be tabulated in the column for free white males of age 16 and under 26.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] The other special counts were foreigners not naturalized, persons engaged in agriculture, persons engaged in commerce, and persons engaged in manufacture.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were also instructed to count each individual in only one of the occupational columns.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] For example, if an individual was engaged in agriculture, commerce, and manufacture, the census taker had to judge which one the individual was primarily engaged in.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and drew up their own, sometimes resulting in pages without headings, line tallies, or column totals.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1830-united-states-census] The **1830 United States census**, the fifth census undertaken in the United States, was conducted on June 1, 1830.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1830-united-states-census] The only loss of census records for 1830 involved some countywide losses in Massachusetts, Maryland, and Mississippi.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1830-united-states-census] It determined the population of the 24 states to be 12,866,020, of which 2,009,043 were slaves.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1830-united-states-census] The center of population was about 170 miles (274 km) west of Washington, D.C. in present-day Grant County, West Virginia.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1830-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York—recorded a population of over 200,000.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1830-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1830 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1840-united-states-census] The **1840 United States census** was the sixth census of the United States.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1840-united-states-census] Conducted by U.S. marshals on June 1, 1840, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 17,069,453 – an increase of 32.7 percent over the 12,866,020 persons enumerated during the 1830 census.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1840-united-states-census] The total population included 2,487,355 slaves.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1840-united-states-census] In 1840, the center of population was about 260 miles (418 km) west of Washington, D.C., near Weston, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1840-united-states-census] This was the last census conducted by U.S. marshals, as starting in 1850 a temporary office would be set up for each census under the purview of the Department of the Interior.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1840-united-states-census] This was due to the Northern members of the Whig Party opposing the controversial claim in the 1840 census that free Black Americans in the Northern United States suffered from a higher degree of "insane" or "idiotic" behavior compared to enslaved Black Americans.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1840-united-states-census] The 1840 census was the first that attempted to count Americans who were "insane" or "idiotic".
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1840-united-states-census] Published results of the census indicated that alarming numbers of black persons living in non-slaveholding States were mentally ill, in striking contrast to the corresponding figures for slaveholding States.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1840-united-states-census] Pro-slavery advocates trumpeted the results as evidence of the beneficial effects of slavery, and the probable consequences of emancipation.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1840-united-states-census] The memorial was submitted to the House of Representatives by John Quincy Adams, who contended that it demonstrated "a multitude of gross and important errors" in the published returns.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1840-united-states-census] In response to the House's request for an inquiry, Secretary of State John C.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1840-united-states-census] Calhoun reported that a careful examination of the statistics by the supervisor of the census had fully sustained their correctness.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1840-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1840 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1840-united-states-census] A compendium of data from the sixth census, organized by States, counties, and principal towns is available on the web site of the Census Bureau.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The **1850 United States census** was the seventh decennial United States Census Conducted by the Census Office, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 23,191,876—an increase of 35.9 percent over the 17,069,453 persons enumerated during the 1840 census.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The total population included 3,204,313 enslaved people.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Although the official date of the census date was June 1, 1850, completed census forms indicate that the surveys continued to be made throughout the rest of the year.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census where there was an attempt to collect information about every member of every household and not only the head of the household.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Slaves were included by gender and estimated age on Slave Schedules, listed by the name of the owner.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Prior to 1850, census records had recorded only the name of the head of the household and broad statistical accounting of other household members (three children under age five, one woman between the age of 35 and 40, etc.).
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This was also the first census to ask about place of birth of free residents.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Hinton Rowan Helper made extensive use of the 1850 census results in his influential anti-slavery book *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857).
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census in which the US recorded a greater population than the United Kingdom (a year later) which it broke off from 65 years prior.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1850 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census collected a great amount of data that gave insight into the state of the U.S. economy in 1850.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Some of the data revealed the growth of the economy with regard to agricultural and manufactured production, international trade, federal debt, taxation, transportation, education, and land expansion.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This census calculated the total land by state (in square miles), the total production of major goods and livestock per state (in respective units), the total value of each good produced, the total number of plantations per state, and various other statistics.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The total agricultural production between in 1850 was calculated at about 1.3 billion dollars.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Total manufactured production was valued at just over one billion dollars.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This is a great increase over the totals estimated in 1820 and 1840.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Also, in total, the manufacturing industry recorded an overall profit of 43%.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census contains the total value of imports and exports by state, statistics and names of the major imports and exports, the total values of shipping by state, and the value of imports and exports with various individual countries.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The United States traded most with the United Kingdom.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The imports and exports with the United Kingdom were both valued around 145 million dollars.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This census contains yearly federal debt totals, total federal revenues, and total expenditures from 1790 to 1853.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The total debt of the United States on July 1, 1854, was roughly 47.2 million dollars.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The census contains some calculation of total annual federal taxes, but it is incomplete.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] It does however, give state taxation totals.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This census calculates the total cost, size, and quantity of railroads and canals.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The funded debt for railroads and canals in 1853 was 130 million.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Their gross earnings were more than 38 million dollars.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This census also contains estimates for growth in mileage of telegraphic lines in the United States.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] of telegraphic lines, a drastic increase.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census shows the great amount of territorial expansion that took place in the United States, following the Admission of Texas, the Oregon Treaty, and the Treaty with Mexico following the war in 1848.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] These three pieces of territory totaled an addition of more than a million square miles to the nation.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] In 1850, the United States contained 31 states and 4 organized territories (Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Utah).
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census can be seen as a historical document that gives insight into the state of the nation's economy in 1850.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] It is much more detailed and provides more information than the 1840 census.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This census was conducted during a very important period of growth and innovation in the United States, the Industrial Revolution.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The statistics in this census provide data on the rate of growth that was taking place in 1850, which resulted in the emergence of the United States as an economic world power.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Many of the statistics were compared to those of Great Britain and other world powers.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This shows where the United States stood economically relative to the rest of the world.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1850 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The Utah Territorial census was taken in 1851.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Secretary Broughton Harris refused to certify the census of Utah Territory.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Harris complained that Brigham Young had conducted the census without him, claimed several irregularities, and consequently withheld funds reserved for the census.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The controversy contributed to Harris' decision to join other Runaway Officials of 1851 and abandon his post in Utah Territory.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Relationships with the federal government continued to sour and eventually resulted in the Utah War.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Local government officials feared having an enslaved population might impede the territory's quest for statehood, since certain members of Congress were concerned about expansion of slavery into the western territories.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census slave schedule for Utah Territory reported only 26 slaves, with a note that all of them were heading to California, and did not include any enslaved people remaining in the territory.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] John David Smith estimates that there were 100 blacks in Utah by 1850, with two-thirds of them enslaved.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Charleston was founded by the English in 1670 as Charles Town, named in honor of King Charles II.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Originally established at Albemarle Point on the west bank of the Ashley River (now Charles Towne Landing), the settlement was moved in 1680 to its present location, where it quickly grew to become the fifth-largest city in North America by the 1690s.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] During the colonial period, Charleston remained unincorporated and was governed by a colonial legislature and a royal governor, with administrative districts and social services organized by Anglican parishes.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Although the state capital was relocated to Columbia in 1788, Charleston remained among the top 10 U.S. cities by population through 1840.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] A significant part of Charleston's history is its central role in the Atlantic slave trade; local merchants, including Joseph Wragg, helped break the monopoly of the Royal African Company, making Charleston a primary entry point for enslaved Africans.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Almost one-half of enslaved people imported to the United States arrived in Charleston.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] In 2018, the city formally apologized for its role in the American slave trade.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The economy of Charleston is anchored by tourism, port and logistics, aerospace, and information technology.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The city is home to the Port of Charleston, one of the busiest in the United States, which significantly contributes to regional trade and economic activity.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Boeing and other major employers have established a strong aerospace presence, while its growing tech industry has led to the nickname "Silicon Harbor".
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Culturally, Charleston is renowned for its well-preserved architecture, historic landmarks, and rich Gullah heritage, alongside vibrant culinary, music, and arts scenes.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Popular attractions include the historic City Market, Fort Sumter National Monument, and antebellum homes along the Battery and Rainbow Row.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The unified Cusabo people (including sub tribes such as Kiawah) and the Ittiwan people inhabited the area prior to colonial settlement.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] They were known as "Settlement Indians" by colonists.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] King Charles II granted the chartered Province of Carolina to eight of his loyal friends, known as the Lords Proprietors, on March 24, 1663.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Later that year, prominent planters from Barbados attempted their first settlement in the Carolinas on the Cape Fear River, building what would become Charles Towne, North Carolina.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] This settlement was short lived and most returned back to Barbados a few years into the enterprise.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] In 1670, Governor William Sayle arranged for several shiploads of settlers from Bermuda and Barbados.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] These settlers established what was then called Charles Town at Albemarle Point, on the west bank of the Ashley River, a few miles northwest of the present-day city center.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Charles Town became the first comprehensively planned town in the Thirteen Colonies.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Its governance, settlement, and development were to follow a visionary plan known as the Grand Model prepared for the Lord's Proprietors by John Locke.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Because the Carolina's Fundamental Constitutions were never ratified, however, Charles Town was never incorporated during the colonial period.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Instead, local ordinances were passed by the provincial government, with day-to-day administration handled by the wardens and vestries of St Philip's and St Michael's Anglican parishes.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] At the time of European colonization, the area was inhabited by the indigenous Cusabo, on whom the settlers declared war in October 1671.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The settlers initially allied with the Westo, a northern indigenous tribe that traded in enslaved Indians.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The settlers abandoned their alliance with the Westo in 1679 and allied with the Cusabo instead.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The initial settlement quickly dwindled and disappeared while another village—established by the settlers on Oyster Point at the confluence of the Ashley and Cooper rivers around 1672—thrived.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] In 1680, this second settlement formally replaced the original Charles Town, which today is commemorated as Charles Towne Landing.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The second location was more defensible and had access to a fine natural harbor.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The new town had become the fifth largest in North America by 1690.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] A smallpox outbreak erupted in 1698, followed by an earthquake in February 1699.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The latter caused a fire that destroyed about a third of the town.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] During rebuilding, a yellow fever outbreak killed about 15% of the remaining inhabitants.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Charles Town suffered between five and eight significant yellow fever outbreaks over the first half of the 18th century.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] It developed a reputation as one of the least healthy locations in the Thirteen Colonies for ethnic Europeans.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Although malaria did not have such high mortality as yellow fever, it caused much illness.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] It was a major health problem throughout most of the city's history before dying out in the 1950s after the use of pesticides cut down on the mosquitoes that transmitted it.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Charles Town was fortified according to a plan developed in 1704 under Governor Nathaniel Johnson.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Both Spain and France contested Britain's claims to the region.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Various bands of Native Americans and independent pirates also raided it.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] On September 5–6, 1713 (O.S.), a violent hurricane passed over Charles Town.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The Circular Congregational Church manse was damaged during the storm, and church records were lost.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Much of Charles Town was flooded as "the Ashley and Cooper rivers became one." At least seventy people died in the disaster.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] From the 1670s, Charleston attracted pirates.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The combination of a weak government and corruption made the city popular with pirates, who frequently visited and raided the city.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Charles Town was besieged by the pirate Blackbeard for several days in May 1718.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Blackbeard released his hostages and left in exchange for a chest of medicine from Governor Robert Johnson.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Around 1719, the town's name began to be generally written as Charlestown and, excepting those fronting the Cooper River, the old walls were largely removed over the next decade.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Charlestown was a center for the inland colonization of South Carolina.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] It remained the southernmost point of the Southern Colonies until the Province of Georgia was established in 1732.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] As noted, the first settlers primarily came from Europe, Barbados and Bermuda.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The Barbadian and Bermudan immigrants were planters who brought enslaved Africans with them, having purchased them in the West Indies.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Early immigrant groups to the city included the Huguenots, Scottish, Irish, and Germans, as well as hundreds of Jews, predominately Sephardi from London and significant cities of the Dutch Republic, where they had been given refuge.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] As late as 1830, Charleston's Jewish community was the most prominent and wealthiest in North America.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] By 1708, most of the colony's population were Black Africans.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] They had been brought to Charlestown via the Atlantic slave trade, first as indentured servants and then as enslaved people.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] In the early 1700s, Charleston's largest slave trader, Joseph Wragg, pioneered the settlement's involvement in the slave trade.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Of the estimated 400,000 captive Africans transported to North America to be sold into slavery, 40% are thought to have landed at Sullivan's Island off Charlestown.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Free people of color also migrated from the West Indies, being descendants of white planters and their Black consorts and unions among the working classes.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] In 1767, Gadsden's Wharf was constructed at the city port on the Cooper River; it ultimately extended 840 feet and could accommodate six ships at a time.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Many enslaved people were sold from here.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] At the foundation of the town, the principal items of commerce were pine timber and pitch for ships and tobacco.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The early economy developed around the deerskin trade, in which colonists used alliances with the Cherokee and Creek peoples to secure the raw material.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] At the same time, Native Americans kidnapped and enslaved each other in warfare.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] From 1680 to 1720, approximately 40,000 native men, women, and children were sold through the port, principally to the West Indies (such as Bermuda and the Bahamas), but also to other Southern colonies.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The Lowcountry planters did not keep enslaved Native Americans, considering them too prone to escape or revolt.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] They used the proceeds of their sale to purchase enslaved Black Africans for their own plantations.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The slave raiding—and the European firearms it introduced—helped destabilize Spanish Florida and French Louisiana in the 1700s during the War of the Spanish Succession.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] But it also provoked the Yamasee War of the 1710s that nearly destroyed the colony.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] After that, South Carolina largely abandoned the Indian slave trade.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The area's unsuitability for growing tobacco prompted the Lowcountry planters to experiment with other cash crops.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The profitability of growing rice led the planters to pay premiums for enslaved people from the "Rice Coast" who knew its cultivation; their descendants make up the ethnic Gullah who created their own culture and language in this area.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Slaves imported from the Caribbean showed the planter George Lucas's daughter Eliza how to raise and use indigo for dyeing in 1747.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Throughout this period, enslaved people were sold aboard the arriving ships or at ad hoc gatherings in the town's taverns.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Runaways and minor slave rebellions prompted the 1739 Security Act, which required all white men to carry weapons at all times (even to church on Sundays).
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Before it fully took effect, the Cato or Stono Rebellion broke out.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The white community had recently been decimated by a malaria outbreak, and the rebels killed about 25 white people before being stopped by the colonial militia.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] As a result of their fears of rebellion, whites killed a total of 35 to 50 Black people.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The planters attributed the violence to recently imported Africans and agreed to a 10-year moratorium on slave importation through Charlestown.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] They relied for labor upon the slave communities they already held.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The 1740 Negro Act also tightened controls, requiring a ratio of one white for every ten Blacks on any plantation (which was often not achieved) and banning enslaved people from assembling, growing personal food, earning money, or learning to read.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Drums were banned because Africans used them for signaling; enslaved people were allowed to use string and other instruments.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] When the moratorium expired and Charlestown reopened to the slave trade in 1750, the memory of the Stono Rebellion resulted in traders avoiding buying enslaved people from the Congo and Angola, whose populations had a reputation for independence.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] By the mid-18th century, Charlestown was the hub of the Atlantic slave trade in the Southern Colonies.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Even with the decade-long moratorium, its customs processed around 40% of the enslaved Africans brought to North America between 1700 and 1775, and about half up until the end of the African trade.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The plantations and the economy based on them made this the wealthiest city in the Thirteen Colonies and the largest in population south of Philadelphia.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] In 1770, the city had 11,000 inhabitants—half enslaved—and was the 4th-largest port in the colonies, after Boston, New York City, and Philadelphia.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The elite began to use their wealth to encourage cultural and social development.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] America's first theater building was constructed in 1736; today's Dock Street Theater later replaced it.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Benevolent societies were formed by the Huguenots, free people of color, Germans, and Jews.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The Library Society was established in 1748 by well-born young men who wanted to share the financial cost of keeping up with the scientific and philosophical issues of the day.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Delegates for the Continental Congress were elected in 1774, and South Carolina declared its independence from Britain on the steps of the Exchange.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Slavery was again an important factor in the city's role during the Revolutionary War.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The British attacked the settlement three times, assuming that the settlement had a large base of Loyalists who would rally to their cause once given some military support.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The Battle of Sullivan's Island saw the British fail to capture a partially constructed palmetto palisade from Col.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Moultrie's militia regiment on June 28, 1776.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The Liberty Flag used by Moultrie's men formed the basis of the later South Carolina flag, and the victory's anniversary continues to be commemorated as Carolina Day.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Making the capture of Charlestown their chief priority, the British sent Sir Henry Clinton, who laid siege to Charleston on April 1, 1780, with about 14,000 troops and 90 ships.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The Patriots, led by Benjamin Lincoln, had about 5,500 men and inadequate fortifications to repel the forces against them.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] After the British cut his supply lines and lines of retreat at the battles of Monck's Corner and Lenud's Ferry, Lincoln's surrender on May 12, 1780, became the greatest American defeat of the war.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The British continued to hold Charlestown for over a year following their defeat at Yorktown in 1781.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] However, they alienated local planters by refusing to restore full civil government.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Nathanael Greene had entered the state after Cornwallis's pyrrhic victory at Guilford Courthouse and kept the area under a kind of siege.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] British Army officer Alexander Leslie, commanding Charlestown, requested a truce in March 1782 to purchase food for his garrison and the town's inhabitants.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Greene refused and formed a brigade under Mordecai Gist to counter British forays.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The British finally evacuated Charlestown in December 1782.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Greene presented the British leaders of the town with the Moultrie Flag.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Between the Revolutionary War and the Civil War, Charleston experienced an economic boom, at least for the top strata of society.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Expanding cotton as a cash crop in the South led to massive wealth for a small segment of society and funded impressive architecture and culture.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] However, it also escalated the economic importance of enslaving people and led to greater and greater restrictions on Black Charlestonians.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] By 1783, the city's growth had reached a point where a municipal government became desirable; therefore, on August 13, 1783, an act of incorporation for Charleston was ratified.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The act originally specified the city's name as "Charles Ton", as opposed to the previous Charlestown, but the spelling "Charleston" quickly came to dominate.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Although Columbia had replaced it as the state capital in 1788, Charleston became even more prosperous as Eli Whitney's 1793 invention of the cotton gin sped the processing of the crop over 50 times.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Britain's Industrial Revolution—initially built upon its textile industry—took up the extra production ravenously and cotton became Charleston's major export commodity in the 19th century.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The Bank of South Carolina, the second-oldest building in the nation to be constructed as a bank, was established in 1798.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] In 1800 and 1817, branches of the First and Second banks were also located in Charleston.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Throughout the Antebellum Period, Charleston continued to be the only major American city with a majority-slave population.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] American traders had been prohibited from equipping the Atlantic slave trade in 1794 and all importation of enslaved people was banned in 1808, but American merchantmen frequently refused to permit British inspection for enslaved cargo, and smuggling remained common.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Much more important was the domestic slave trade, which boomed as the Deep South developed into new cotton plantations.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] As a result of the trade, there was a forced migration of more than one million enslaved people from the Upper South to the Lower South in the antebellum years.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] During the early 19th century, the first dedicated slave markets were founded in Charleston, mostly near Chalmers and State streets.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Many domestic slavers used Charleston as a port in the coastwise trade, traveling to such ports as Mobile and New Orleans.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Enslaving was the primary marker of class, and even the town's freedmen and free people of color typically enslaved people if they had the wealth to do so.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Visitors commonly remarked on the sheer number of Blacks in Charleston and their seeming freedom of movement, though in fact—mindful of the Stono Rebellion and the slave revolution that established Haiti—the whites closely regulated the behavior of both enslaved and free people of color.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The town fixed wages and hiring practices, sometimes required identifying badges, and sometimes censored work songs.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Punishment was handled out of sight by the city's workhouse, whose fees provided the municipal government with thousands a year.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] In 1820, state law mandated that each act of manumission (freeing an enslaved person) required legislative approval, effectively halting the practice.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The effects of slavery were pronounced on white society as well.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The white middle class was minimal: Charlestonians generally looked down upon hard work, considering it as labor meant for enslaved people.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] All the enslavers taken together held 82% of the city's wealth and almost all non-enslavers were poor.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Olmsted considered their civic elections "entirely contests of money and personal influence" and the oligarchs dominated civic planning: The lack of public parks and amenities was noted, as was the abundance of private gardens in the wealthy's walled estates.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] In the 1810s, the town's churches intensified their discrimination against their Black parishioners, culminating in Bethel Methodist's 1817 construction of a hearse house over its Black burial ground.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] 4,376 Black Methodists joined Morris Brown in establishing Hampstead Church, the African Methodist Episcopal church now known as Mother Emanuel.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] State and city laws prohibited Black literacy, limited Black worship to daylight hours, and required a majority of any church's parishioners be white.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] In June 1818, 140 Black church members at Hampstead Church were arrested, and eight of its leaders were given fines and ten lashes; police raided the church again in 1820 and pressured it in 1821.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] In 1822, members of the church, led by Denmark Vesey, a lay preacher and carpenter who had bought his freedom after winning a lottery, planned an uprising and escape to Haiti—initially for Bastille Day—that failed when one enslaved person revealed the plot to his enslaver.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Over the next month, the city's intendant (mayor) James Hamilton Jr. organized a militia for regular patrols, initiated a secret and extrajudicial tribunal to investigate, and hanged 35 and exiled 35 or 37 enslaved people to Spanish Cuba for their involvement.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] This structure later was the basis of the Citadel's first campus.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The AME congregation built a new church, but in 1834, the city banned it and all Black worship services following Nat Turner's Rebellion in Virginia in 1831.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The estimated 10% of enslaved people who came to America as Muslims never had a separate mosque.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Enslavers sometimes provided them with beef rations instead of pork in recognition of religious traditions.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The Charleston Fire Scare of 1826 began on Christmas Eve 1825 when an arson fire on King Street caused over $80,000 worth of damage.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] For more than the next six months, until mid-June, fires were started night after night, sometimes as many as 5 fires at a time, devastating the city's wooden architecture.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The city council offered a reward of $1000 for the capture of arsonists, who the white population believed to be slaves or Free Blacks; an angry crowd almost lynched some suspected culprits.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] At least 3 Blacks were convicted in connection with the fires.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The final blaze caused another $100,000 in damage, again on King Street.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Coming so soon after the Vesey Rebellion, the Fire Scare caused unease among the white population of the city.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] This underlined the fact that servile rebellion did not necessarily require great ingenuity and skill to effectively strike back at the enslavers of Blacks.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The registered tonnage of Charleston shipping in 1829 was 12,410.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] In 1832, South Carolina passed an ordinance of nullification, a procedure by which a state could, in effect, repeal a federal law; it was directed against the most recent tariff acts.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The state's politicians worked on a compromise law in Washington to gradually reduce the tariffs.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Charleston's embrace of classical architecture began after a devastating fire leveled much of the city.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] On April 27, 1838, Charleston suffered a catastrophic fire that burned more than 1000 buildings and caused about $3 million (equivalent to $87,139,000 in 2024) in damage at the time.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The damaged buildings amounted to about one-fourth of all the businesses in the main part of the city.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] A great cultural awakening occurred when many homes and businesses were rebuilt or repaired.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Before the fire, few homes were styled as Greek Revival; many residents decided to construct new buildings in that style after the conflagration.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] This tradition continued, making Charleston one of the foremost places to view Greek Revival architecture.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The Gothic Revival also made a significant appearance in the construction of many churches after the fire that exhibited picturesque forms and reminders of devout European religion.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] By 1840, the Market Hall and Sheds, where fresh meat and produce were brought daily, became a hub of commercial activity.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The slave trade also depended on the port of Charleston, where ships could be unloaded and enslaved people bought and sold.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The legal importation of enslaved Africans had ended in 1808, although smuggling was significant.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] However, the domestic trade was booming.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] More than one million enslaved people were transported from the Upper South to the Deep South in the antebellum years, as cotton plantations were widely developed through what became known as the Black Belt.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Many enslaved people were transported in the coastwise slave trade, with slave ships stopping at ports such as Charleston.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Charleston was significant in the American Civil War.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Army and Confederate States Army vied for control of it.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The rebellion began in Charleston Harbor in 1861 and ended mere months after the U.S. soldiers retook control of Charleston in 1865.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Following the election of Abraham Lincoln, the South Carolina General Assembly voted on December 20, 1860, to declare secession from the United States, becoming the first state to do so.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Army garrison of Castle Pinckney surrendered to the state militia.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] On January 9, 1861, Citadel cadets opened fire on the USS *Star of the West* as it entered Charleston Harbor.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The first full battle of the war occurred on April 12, 1861, when shore batteries under the command of General P.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Beauregard fired upon the US Army-held Fort Sumter in Charleston Harbor.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] After a 34-hour bombardment, Major Robert Anderson surrendered the fort.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] On December 11, 1861, an enormous fire burned over 500 acres (200 ha) of the city.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Navy control of the North Atlantic coastline permitted the repeated bombardment of the city, causing vast damage.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Although Admiral Du Pont's naval assault on the town's forts in April 1863 failed, the U.S.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Navy's blockade shut down most commercial traffic.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Throughout the war, some blockade runners got through, but not a single one made it into or out of Charleston Harbor between August 1863 and March 1864.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Hunley* made a night attack on the USS *Housatonic* on February 17, 1864.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] General Gillmore's land assault in July 1864 was unsuccessful but the fall of Columbia and advance of General William T.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Sherman's army through the state prompted the Confederates to evacuate the town on February 17, 1865, burning the public buildings, cotton warehouses, and other sources of supply before their departure.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] U.S. soldiers moved into the city within the month.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The War Department recovered what federal property remained.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Also, it confiscated the campus of the Citadel Military Academy and used it as a U.S.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The facilities were finally returned to the state and reopened as a military college in 1882 under the direction of Lawrence E.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] After the defeat of the Confederacy, U.S. soldiers remained in Charleston during the Reconstruction era.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The war had shattered the city's prosperity.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Still, the African-American population surged (from 17,000 in 1860 to over 27,000 in 1880) as freedmen moved from the countryside to the major city.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Blacks quickly left the Southern Baptist Church and resumed open meetings of the African Methodist Episcopal and AME Zion churches.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] They purchased dogs, guns, liquor, and better clothes—all previously banned—and ceased yielding the sidewalks to whites.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Despite the efforts of the state legislature to halt manumissions, Charleston had already had a large class of free people of color as well.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] At the onset of the war, the city had 3,785 free people of color, many of mixed race, making up about 18% of the city's Black population and 8% of its total population.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Many were educated and practiced skilled crafts; they quickly became leaders of South Carolina's Republican Party and its legislators.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Free men of color comprised 26% of those elected to state and federal office in South Carolina from 1868 to 1876.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The Pacific Guano Company, established in 1861, opened a plant in Charleston which consumed immense quantities of menhaden scrap brought from the water by the vessels which carried on their return trip a supply of South Carolina phosphates for the Woods Hole, Massachusetts factory.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] By the late 1870s, industry was bringing the city and its inhabitants back to a renewed vitality; new jobs attracted new residents.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] As the city's commerce improved, residents worked to restore or create community institutions.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] In 1865, the Avery Normal Institute was established by the American Missionary Association as the first free secondary school for Charleston's African American population.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Sherman lent his support to the conversion of the United States Arsenal into the Porter Military Academy, an educational facility for former soldiers and boys left orphaned or destitute by the war.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Porter Military Academy later joined with Gaud School and is now a university-preparatory school, Porter-Gaud School.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] In 1875, Black people made up 57% of the city's and 73% of the county's population.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] With leadership by members of the antebellum free Black community, historian Melinda Meeks Hennessy described the community as "unique" in being able to defend themselves without provoking "massive white retaliation", as occurred in numerous other areas during Reconstruction.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] In the 1876 election cycle, two major riots between Black Republicans and white Democrats occurred in the city, in September and the day after the election in November, as well as a violent incident in Cainhoy at an October joint discussion meeting.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Violent incidents occurred throughout the Piedmont of the state as white insurgents struggled to impose white supremacy in the face of social changes after the war and the granting of citizenship to freedmen by amendments to the U.S.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] After former Confederates were allowed to vote again, election campaigns from 1872 on were marked by violent intimidation of Black people and Republicans by conservative Democratic paramilitary groups, known as the Red Shirts.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Violent incidents occurred in Charleston on King Street on September 6 and nearby Cainhoy on October 15 in association with political meetings before the 1876 election.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The Cainhoy incident was the only one statewide in which more whites were killed than black people.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The Red Shirts were instrumental in suppressing the Black Republican vote in some areas in 1876 and narrowly electing Wade Hampton as governor, and taking back control of the state legislature.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Another riot occurred in Charleston the day after the election when a prominent Republican leader was mistakenly reported killed.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] In the early 20th century, strong political machines emerged in the city, reflecting economic, class, racial, and ethnic tensions.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Senator Ben Tillman who repeatedly attacked and ridiculed the city in the name of upstate poor farmers.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Well-organized factions within the Democratic Party in Charleston gave the voters clear choices and played a large role in state politics.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] On August 31, 1886, Charleston experienced a strong earthquake.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The shock was estimated to have a moment magnitude of 7.0 and a maximum Mercalli intensity of X (*Extreme*).
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] It was felt as far away as Boston to the north, Chicago and Milwaukee to the northwest, as far west as New Orleans, as far south as Cuba, and as far east as Bermuda.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] It damaged 2,000 buildings in Charleston and caused $6 million worth of damage ($185 million in 2024 dollars), at a time when all the city's buildings were valued around $24 million ($738 million in 2024 dollars).
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The Charleston race riot of 1919 took place on the night of Saturday, May 10, between members of the US Navy and the local Black population.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] They attacked Black individuals, businesses, and homes, killing six and injuring dozens.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Charleston languished economically for several decades in the 20th century, though the large federal military presence in the region helped to shore up the city's economy.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Charleston's tourism boom began in earnest following the publication of Albert Simons and Samuel Lapham's *Architecture of Charleston* in the 1920s.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The Charleston Hospital Strike of 1969, in which mostly Black workers protested discrimination and low wages, was one of the last major events of the civil rights movement.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] It attracted Ralph Abernathy, Coretta Scott King, Andrew Young, and other prominent figures to march with the local leader, Mary Moultrie.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The 1969 Charleston hospital strike was built on generations of community-building and activism within Charleston's Black, working-class neighborhoods.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Notably, activists from former labor struggles provided guidance for the hospital strike; for example, Lillie Mae Doster and Isaiah Bennett, participants of the 1945-1946 Cigar Factory Strike in Charleston, shared their experience and resources with hospital strikers in 1969.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Riley Jr. was elected mayor in the 1970s and helped advance several cultural aspects of the city.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Between 1989 and 1996, Charleston saw two significant economic hits.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] First, the eye of Hurricane Hugo came ashore at Charleston Harbor in 1989, and though the worst damage was in nearby McClellanville, three-quarters of the homes in Charleston's historic district sustained damage of varying degrees.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The hurricane caused over $2.8 billion in damage.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The city rebounded fairly quickly after the hurricane and has grown in population, reaching an estimated 124,593 residents in 2009.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Second, in 1993, the Base Realignment and Closure Commission (BRAC) directed that Naval Base Charleston be closed.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Pursuant to BRAC action, Naval Base Charleston was closed on April 1, 1996, although some activities remain under the cognizance of Naval Support Activity Charleston, now part of Joint Base Charleston.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] After having been a majority-minority city for most of its history, in the late 20th century, many whites began returning to the urban core of Charleston, and the area gentrified with rising prices and rents.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] From 1980 to 2010, the peninsula's population shifted from two-thirds Black to two-thirds white; in 2010, residents numbered 20,668 whites and 10,455 Blacks.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Many African Americans moved to the less-expensive suburbs in these decades.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] On June 17, 2015, 21-year-old white supremacist Dylann Roof entered the historic Emanuel African Methodist Episcopal Church and sat in on part of a Bible study before shooting and killing nine people and injuring a tenth, all African Americans.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Senior pastor Clementa Pinckney, who also served as a state senator, was among those killed during the attack.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The deceased also included congregation members Susie Jackson, 87; Rev.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Daniel Simmons Sr., 74; Ethel Lance, 70; Myra Thompson, 59; Cynthia Hurd, 54; Rev.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Sharonda Coleman-Singleton, 45; and Tywanza Sanders, 26.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The attack garnered national attention and sparked a debate on racism, Confederate symbolism in Southern states, and gun violence, in part based on Roof's online postings.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] A memorial service on the campus of the College of Charleston was attended by President Barack Obama, Michelle Obama, Vice President Joe Biden, Jill Biden, and Speaker of the House John Boehner.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] On June 17, 2018, the Charleston City Council apologized for its role in the slave trade and condemned its "inhumane" history.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] It also acknowledged wrongs committed against African Americans by slavery and Jim Crow laws.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The city proper consists of six distinct districts.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The incorporated city fit into 4–5 sq mi (10–13 km2) as late as World War I, but has since greatly expanded, crossing the Ashley River and encompassing James Island and some of Johns Island.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The city limits also have expanded across the Cooper River, encompassing Daniel Island and the Cainhoy area.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] North Charleston blocks any expansion up the peninsula, and Mount Pleasant occupies the land directly east of the Cooper River.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Charleston Harbor runs about 7 miles (11 km) southeast to the Atlantic with an average width of about 2 miles (3.2 km), surrounded on all sides except its entrance.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Sullivan's Island lies to the north of the entrance and Morris Island to the south.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The entrance itself is about 1 mi (2 km) wide; it was originally only 18 ft (5 m) deep but began to be enlarged in the 1870s.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The tidal rivers (Wando, Cooper, Stono, and Ashley) are evidence of a submergent or drowned coastline.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] There is a submerged river delta off the mouth of the harbor, and the Cooper River is deep.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Charleston has a humid subtropical climate (Köppen climate classification *Cfa*), with mild winters, hot humid summers, and significant rainfall all year long.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Summer is the wettest season; almost half of the annual rainfall occurs from June to September in the form of thundershowers.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Fall remains relatively warm through the middle of November.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Winter is short and mild and is characterized by occasional rain.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Measurable snow (≥0.1 in or 0.25 cm) has a median occurrence of only once per decade at the airport, but freezing rain is more common; a snowfall/freezing rain event on January 3, 2018, was the first such event in Charleston since December 26, 2010.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] However, 6.0 in (15 cm) fell at the airport on December 23, 1989, during the December 1989 United States cold wave, the largest single-day fall on record, contributing to a single-storm and seasonal record of 8.0 in (20 cm) snowfall.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Downtown Charleston's climate is milder than the airport's due to more substantial maritime influence.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] This is especially true in the winter, with the average January low in downtown being 43.6 °F (6 °C) to the airport's 38.9 °F (4 °C) for example.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The highest temperature recorded within city limits was 104 °F (40 °C) on June 2, 1985, and June 24, 1944; the lowest was 7 °F (−14 °C) on February 14, 1899, although there was an unofficial record low of 1 °F (−17 °C) in February 1835.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] At the airport, where official records are kept, the historical range is 105 °F (41 °C) on August 1, 1999, down to 6 °F (−14 °C) on January 21, 1985.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Hurricanes are a major threat to the area during the summer and early fall, with several severe hurricanes hitting the area—most notably Hurricane Hugo on September 21, 1989 (a category 4 storm).
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The dewpoint from June to August ranges from 67.8 to 71.4 °F (19.9 to 21.9 °C).
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] As defined by the Office of Management and Budget, for use by the U.S.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Government agencies for statistical purposes only, Charleston is included within the Charleston-North Charleston, SC Metropolitan Statistical Area, which consists of three counties: Charleston, Berkeley, and Dorchester.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The metropolitan statistical area had an estimated population of 849,417 in 2023.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] North Charleston is the second-largest city in the metro area and ranks as the third-largest city in the state; Mount Pleasant and Summerville are the next-largest cities.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] The traditional parish system persisted until counties were established during the Reconstruction Era.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Nevertheless, traditional parishes still exist in various capacities, mainly as public service districts.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] When the city of Charleston was formed, it was defined by the limits of the Parish of St.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] Michael, which now also includes parts of St.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p01] However, the last two are mostly still incorporated rural parishes.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] As of the 2020 census, Charleston had a population of 150,227.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] 17.8% of residents were under the age of 18 and 15.9% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] For every 100 females there were 91.3 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 88.5 males age 18 and over.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] 98.2% of residents lived in urban areas, while 1.8% lived in rural areas.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] There were 67,675 households in Charleston, of which 22.5% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Of all households, 38.3% were married-couple households, 20.8% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 33.5% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] About 34.9% of all households were made up of individuals and 10.8% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] There were 77,479 dwelling units, of which 12.7% were vacant.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The homeowner vacancy rate was 2.2% and the rental vacancy rate was 12.9%.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] In 2023, of the 150,227 people in Charleston, about 134,996 of them lived in Charleston County, and 15,231 of them lived in Berkeley County.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Charleston historically had a large concentration of African Americans who spoke Gullah, a creole language that developed on the Sea Islands and in the Low Country, and local speech patterns were also influenced by this community.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Today, Gullah is still spoken by some African-American residents.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] However, rapid development since 1980, especially on the surrounding Sea Islands, has attracted residents from outside the area and led to a decline in Gullah's prominence.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The traditional educated Charleston accent has long been noted throughout the state and South.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] It is typically heard in wealthy European American older people who trace their families back generations in the city.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] It has ingliding or monophthongal long mid-vowels, raises *ay* and *aw* in certain environments, and is nonrhotic.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Sylvester Primer of the College of Charleston wrote about aspects of the local dialect in his late 19th-century works: "Charleston Provincialisms" (1887) and "The Huguenot Element in Charleston's Provincialisms", published in a German journal.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] He believed the accent was based on English, as the earliest settlers spoke it; therefore, it was derived from Elizabethan England and preserved with modifications by Charleston speakers.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The disappearing "Charleston accent" spoken mainly by older natives is still noted in the local pronunciation of the city's name.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Many Charleston natives ignore the 'r' and elongate the first vowel, pronouncing the name as "Chalston".
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Despite beliefs that the term dates to the city's earliest days and refers to its religiously tolerant culture, the expression was coined in the 20th century, likely as a mockery of Charlestonians' self-satisfied attitude about their city.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Many sources, however, traditionally link the term to the many old church spires dotting the skyline of downtown Charleston.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Regardless of the nickname's origin, residents have embraced the term and have explained it in more flattering ways.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The Anglican church was dominant in the colonial era, and the Cathedral of St.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Paul is today the seat of the Anglican Diocese of South Carolina.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] John's Protestant Episcopal Church is another historic church in Charleston.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Many French Huguenot refugees settled in Charleston in the early 18th century.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The Emanuel African Methodist Episcopal Church is the oldest African Methodist Episcopal church in the Southern United States and houses the oldest black congregation south of Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] South Carolina has long allowed Jews to practice their faith without restriction.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Kahal Kadosh Beth Elohim, founded in 1749 by Sephardic Jews from London, is the fourth-oldest Jewish congregation in the continental United States and was an important site for the development of Reform Judaism.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Brith Sholom Beth Israel is the oldest Orthodox synagogue in the South, founded by Sam Berlin and other Ashkenazi German and Central European Jews in the mid-19th century.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Mary of the Annunciation Catholic Church is the mother church of Catholicism in South Carolina, North Carolina, and Georgia.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] In 1820, Charleston was established as the see city of the Diocese of Charleston, which at the time comprised the Carolinas and Georgia and presently encompasses the state of South Carolina.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The Supreme Council of the Scottish Rite, established in Charleston in 1801, is considered the mother council of the world by Scottish Rite Freemasons.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Charleston's culture blends traditional Southern U.S., English, French, and West African elements.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The downtown peninsula has several arts, music, local cuisine, and fashion venues.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Spoleto Festival USA, held annually in late spring, was founded in 1977 by Pulitzer Prize–winning composer Gian Carlo Menotti, who sought to establish a counterpart to the *Festival dei Due Mondi* (the Festival of Two Worlds) in Spoleto, Italy.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Charleston's oldest community theater group, the Footlight Players, has provided theatrical productions since 1931.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] A variety of performing arts venues includes the historic Dock Street Theatre.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The annual Charleston Fashion Week held each spring in Marion Square brings in designers, journalists, and clients nationwide.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The cuisine in Charleston is strongly influenced by British, French, and Gullah elements.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The city is known for dishes such as shrimp and grits, she-crab soup, fried oysters, Lowcountry boil, deviled crab cakes, and red rice.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Local seafood—especially oysters, blue crab, shrimp, flounder, and black sea bass—features prominently due to the region's estuaries and marshes.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Gullah Geechee foodways continue to shape Charleston's culinary identity through staples like Carolina Gold rice, okra, field peas, and benne seeds, reflecting the agricultural knowledge brought by enslaved West Africans.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] In the twenty-first century, Charleston has become a nationally recognized dining destination, with a growing number of award-winning restaurants and chefs contributing to its modern food scene.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] As of November 2025, Charleston is home to three restaurants awarded one Michelin star.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Charleston annually hosts Spoleto Festival USA founded by Gian Carlo Menotti, a 17-day art festival featuring over 100 performances by individual artists in various disciplines.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The annual Piccolo Spoleto festival takes place at the same time and features local performers and artists, with hundreds of performances throughout the city.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The Charleston Conference is a major library industry event, held in the city center since 1980.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The Gullah community has had a tremendous influence on music in Charleston, especially when it comes to the early development of jazz music.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] In turn, Charleston's music has influenced the rest of the country.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The geechee dances that accompanied the music of the dock workers in Charleston followed a rhythm that inspired Eubie Blake's "Charleston Rag" and later James P.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Johnson's "Charleston", as well as the dance craze that defined a nation in the 1920s.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] "Ballin' the Jack", which was a popular dance in the years before "Charleston", was written by native Charlestonian Chris Smith.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The Jenkins Orphanage was established in 1891 by the Rev.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The orphanage accepted donations of musical instruments, and Rev.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Jenkins hired local Charleston musicians and Avery Institute Graduates to tutor the boys in music.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] As a result, Charleston musicians became proficient on various instruments and could read music expertly.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] These traits set Jenkins musicians apart and helped land some of them positions in big bands with Duke Ellington and Count Basie.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] William "Cat" Anderson, Jabbo Smith, and Freddie Green are but a few of the alumni who became professional musicians.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Orphanages around the country began to develop brass bands in the wake of the Jenkins Orphanage Band's success.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] As many as five bands were on tour during the 1920s.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The Jenkins Orphanage Band played in the inaugural parades of Presidents Theodore Roosevelt and William Taft and toured the US and Europe.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The band also played on Broadway for the play "Porgy" by DuBose and Dorothy Heyward, a stage version of their novel of the same title.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The story was based in Charleston and featured the Gullah community.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The Heywards insisted on hiring the genuine Jenkins Orphanage Band to portray themselves on stage.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Only a few years later, DuBose Heyward collaborated with George and Ira Gershwin to turn his novel into the now famous opera, *Porgy and Bess* (so named to distinguish it from the play).
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] George Gershwin and Heyward spent the summer of 1934 at Folly Beach outside of Charleston writing this "folk opera", as Gershwin called it.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] *Porgy and Bess* is considered one of the first Great American Operas and is widely performed.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] To this day, Charleston is home to many musicians in all genres.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] For example, Heyrocco is a local indie band.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Charleston has a vibrant theater scene, home to America's first theater.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Most of the theaters are part of the League of Charleston Theatres, better known as Theatre Charleston.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Various books and films have been set in Charleston; some of the best-known works are listed below.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] In addition, Charleston is a popular filming location for movies and television, both in its own right and as a stand-in for Southern historical settings.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Commercial shipping is important to the economy.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The city has two shipping terminals, of a total of five terminals owned and operated by the South Carolina Ports Authority in the Charleston metropolitan area, which are part of the fourth-largest container seaport on the East Coast and the seventh-largest container seaport in the United States.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The port is also used to transfer cars and car parts for Charleston's auto manufacturing business, such as Mercedes and Volvo.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Sometimes known as Silicon Harbor, the city is becoming a popular location for high tech and innovation, and this sector has had the highest rate of growth between 2011 and 2012, due in large part to the Charleston Digital Corridor.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] In 2013, the Milken Institute ranked the Charleston region as the ninth-best performing economy in the US because of its growing IT sector.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Notable companies include Blackbaud, Greystar Real Estate Partners, Evening Post Industries, Le Creuset, SPARC a Booz Allen Hamilton subsidiary, BoomTown, CSS, and Benefitfocus.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Charleston has a strong mayor–council government, with the mayor acting as the chief administrator and the executive officer of the municipality.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The mayor also presides over city council meetings and has a vote, the same as other council members.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The current mayor, since 2024, is Republican William S.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The council has 12 members who are each elected from single-member districts.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The City of Charleston Fire Department consists of over 300 full-time firefighters.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] These firefighters operate out of 21 companies located throughout the city: 16 engine companies, two tower companies, two ladder companies, a heavy rescue company, a HAZ-MAT unit, and several special units.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Training, Fire Marshall, Operations, and Administration are the department's divisions.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The department operates on a 24/48 schedule and is a Class 1 ISO rating.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Russell (Rusty) Thomas served as Fire Chief until June 2008, and was succeeded by Chief Thomas Carr in November 2008.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Chief Daniel Curia presently leads the department.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The City of Charleston Police Department, with 456 sworn officers and 117 civilians is South Carolina's largest police department.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Chico Walker serves as the current Chief of Police.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] He follows Luther Reynolds, Greg Mullen and Reuben Greenberg.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Chief Reynolds is credited with continuing successful community outreach programs such as The Illumination Project and fostering a culture of mutual respect.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Under Chief Reynolds, the agency has successfully withstood challenges such as the Coronavirus and downtown disturbances.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Additionally, the agency continues to recruit police candidates in a competitive market.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Emergency medical services (EMS) for the city are provided by Charleston County Emergency Medical Services (CCEMS) & Berkeley County Emergency Medical Services (BCEMS).
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The city is served by the EMS and 911 services of both Charleston and Berkeley counties since the city is part of both counties.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Charleston is the primary medical center for the eastern portion of the state.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The city has several major hospitals located in the downtown area: Medical University of South Carolina Medical Center (MUSC), Ralph H.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Johnson VA Medical Center, and Roper Hospital.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] MUSC is the state's first school of medicine, the largest medical university in the state, and the sixth-oldest continually operating school of medicine in the United States.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The downtown medical district is experiencing rapid growth of biotechnology and medical research industries coupled with substantial expansions of all the major hospitals.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Additionally, more expansions are planned or underway at another major hospital located in the West Ashley portion of the city: Bon Secours-St Francis Xavier Hospital.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The Trident Regional Medical Center located in the City of North Charleston and East Cooper Regional Medical Center located in Mount Pleasant also serve the needs of residents of the city of Charleston.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Coast Guard Station Charleston responds to search and rescue emergencies, conducts maritime law enforcement activities, and performs ports, waterways, and coastal security (PWCS) missions.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Personnel from Station Charleston are highly trained professionals, composed of federal law enforcement officers, boat crew members, and coxswains capable of completing various missions.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] In 2020, the Coast Guard announced plans to construct a 2,800-acre (11 km2) "superbase" on the former Charleston Naval Shipyard complex to consolidate all its Charleston-area facilities and become the homeport for five Security cutters and additional offshore cutters.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Construction began on the Superbase in 2024.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The following table shows Charleston's crime rate for six crimes that Morgan Quitno uses to calculate the ranking of "America's most dangerous cities" in comparison to the national average.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The statistics shown are for the number of crimes committed per 100,000 people.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Since 1999, the overall crime rate in Charleston has declined markedly.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Charleston's total crime index rate in 1999 was 597.1 crimes committed per 100,000 people, while in 2011, the total crime index rate was 236.4 per 100,000.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The city of Charleston is served by the Charleston International Airport.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] It is located in the city of North Charleston and is about 12 mi (19 km) northwest of downtown Charleston.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] It is the busiest passenger airport in South Carolina (IATA: **CHS**, ICAO: **KCHS**).
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The airport shares runways with the adjacent Charleston Air Force Base.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Charleston Executive Airport is a smaller airport located in Charleston's John's Island section and is used by noncommercial aircraft.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Both airports are owned and operated by the Charleston County Aviation Authority.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] As of April 2019, British Airways does seasonal non-stop flights from Charleston to London-Heathrow.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Charleston is served by two daily Amtrak trains: The Palmetto and Silver Meteor at the Amtrak station, located at 4565 Gaynor Avenue in the city of North Charleston, which is approximately 7.5 miles from downtown Charleston.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] I-26 begins in Downtown Charleston, with exits to the Septima Clark Expressway, the Arthur Ravenel Jr.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Heading northwest, it connects the city to North Charleston, the Charleston International Airport, I-95, and Columbia.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Bridge and Septima Clark Expressway are part of US 17, which travels east–west through Charleston and Mount Pleasant.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The Mark Clark Expressway, or I-526, is the bypass around the city and begins and ends at US 17.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] US 52 is Meeting Street and its spur is East Bay Street, which becomes Morrison Drive after leaving the east side.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] This highway merges with King Street in the city's Neck area (industrial district).
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] US 78 is King Street in the downtown merging with Meeting Street.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Bridge across the Cooper River opened on July 16, 2005, and was the longest cable-stayed bridge in the Americas at the time of its construction.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The bridge links downtown Charleston with Mount Pleasant, and has eight lanes plus a 12-foot lane shared by pedestrians and bicycles.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The bridge's height varies but is estimated at 573 feet.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] It replaced the Grace Memorial Bridge (built in 1929) and the Silas N.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] They were considered two of the more dangerous bridges in America and were demolished after the Ravenel Bridge opened.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The city is also served by a bus system operated by the Charleston Area Regional Transportation Authority (CARTA).
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Most of the urban area is served by regional fixed-route buses equipped with bike racks as part of the system's Rack and Ride program.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] CARTA offers connectivity to historic downtown attractions and accommodations with the Downtown Area Shuttle trolley buses, and it offers curbside pickup for disabled passengers with its Tel-A-Ride buses.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] A bus rapid transit system is in development, called Lowcountry Rapid Transit, that will connect Charleston to Summerville through North Charleston.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Rural parts of the city and metropolitan area are served by a different bus system operated by the Berkeley-Charleston-Dorchester Rural Transportation Management Association.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The system is also commonly called the TriCounty Link.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The Port of Charleston, owned and operated by the South Carolina Ports Authority, is one of the largest ports in the United States, ranked seventh in the top 25 by containerized cargo volume in 2018.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] It consists of six terminals, with the sixth opening in April 2021.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Port activity at the two terminals located in the city of Charleston is one of the city's leading sources of revenue, behind tourism.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Today, the Port of Charleston boasts the deepest water in the southeast region and regularly handles ships too big to transit through the Panama Canal.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] A harbor-deepening project was completed, which makes the Port of Charleston's entrance channel a depth of 54 feet (16 m) and harbor channel 52 feet at mean low tide.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] With an average high tide of 6 feet (1.8 m), the depth clearances will become 60 feet (18 m) and 58 feet, respectively.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] At 52 feet (16 m), the Port of Charleston is the deepest harbor on the East Coast.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Part of Union Pier Terminal in Charleston is a cruise ship passenger terminal hosting numerous cruise departures annually through 2019.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Beginning in May 2019, until cruise operations were interrupted in April 2020, the Carnival *Sunshine* was permanently stationed in Charleston, offering 4, 5, and 7-day cruises to the Caribbean.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] With the closure of the Naval Base and the Charleston Naval Shipyard in 1996, Detyens, Inc. signed a long-term lease.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Detyens Shipyard, Inc. is one of the East Coast's most extensive commercial marine repair facilities, with three dry docks, one floating dock, and six piers.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Projects include military, commercial, and cruise ships.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Because most of the city of Charleston is located in Charleston County, it is served by the Charleston County School District, which covers all of Charleston County.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Part of the city, however, is served by the Berkeley County School District, which covers all of Berkeley County.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] This Berkeley County section includes northern portions of the city, such as the Cainhoy Industrial District, Cainhoy Historical District, and Daniel Island.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Bishop England, Porter-Gaud School, and Ashley Hall are the city's oldest and most prominent private schools and are a significant part of Charleston's history, dating back some 150 years.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Public institutions of higher education in Charleston include the College of Charleston, The Citadel, The Military College of South Carolina, and the Medical University of South Carolina.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The city is also home to private schools, including the Charleston Southern University and Charleston School of Law.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Charleston is also home to the Roper Hospital School of Practical Nursing, and the city has a downtown satellite campus for the region's technical school, Trident Technical College.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Charleston has the only college in the country that offers bachelor's degrees in the building arts, The American College of the Building Arts.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Charleston is the nation's 89th-largest Designated market area (DMA), with 332,770 households and 0.27% of the U.S.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The relationship with Spoleto began when Pulitzer Prize-winning Italian composer Gian Carlo Menotti selected Charleston as the city to host the American version of Spoleto's annual Festival of Two Worlds.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] "Looking for a city that would provide the charm of Spoleto, as well as its wealth of theaters, churches, and other performance spaces, they selected Charleston, South Carolina, as the ideal location.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Charleston is also twinned with Speightstown.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] The first colonists to settle in the region designed the original parts of Charlestown based on the plans of Barbados's capital city, Bridgetown.
[src:charleston-south-carolina/charleston-south-carolina-p02] Many indigo, tobacco, and cotton planters relocated their plantation operations and the people they enslaved from Speightstown to Charleston after the sugarcane industry came to dominate agricultural production in Barbados.
